This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.

Summary:
1. Primary Request and Intent:
   The user invoked me as the "Yoke backend engineer" to implement `feat-scheduler` for the Yoke project. The feature spec describes the Scheduler as the orchestration loop wired into `yoke start` that: calls `buildCrashRecovery` on startup, enters a poll/event loop reading SQLite for runnable items, assembles prompts via `PromptAssembler`, creates worktrees via `WorktreeManager`, spawns sessions via `ProcessManager`, feeds stdout through `StreamJsonParser`, fires `applyItemTransition` on every classifier event, runs pre/post commands via `PrePostRunner`, and broadcasts state changes as WS frames. The user also required: injectable deps (ProcessManager, WorktreeManager, PromptAssembler, PrePostRunner), no direct db.writer in scheduler.ts, re-read SQLite on every tick, concurrency counted from SQLite, SIGINT/SIGTERM graceful drain. At completion, update progress.md and handoff.json.

2. Key Technical Concepts:
   - State machine transitions: `pending→ready→bootstrapping→in_progress→complete` (and retry/rate-limited paths)
   - `applyItemTransition(params)` — sole SQLite mutation path for item state
   - `buildCrashRecovery(db)` — detects stale sessions from prior runs, writes `recovery_state` to workflow rows
   - `ingestWorkflow(db, config)` — seeds workflow + item rows from ResolvedConfig at startup
   - `WsClientRegistry` — tracks WS subscriptions, enables scheduler broadcast without importing sockets
   - `SessionSeqStore` + `BackfillBuffer` — monotonic seq per session, in-memory ring buffer for reconnects
   - `insertSession` / `updateSessionPid` / `endSession` — engine-layer SQLite helpers so scheduler never calls db.writer directly
   - `StreamJsonParser` — NDJSON parser emitting `stream.*`, `rate_limit_detected`, `parse_error` events
   - `openSessionLog(db, opts)` — creates JSONL log file and writes `session_log_path` to SQLite atomically
   - Poll loop with `setTimeout` (default 500ms), `inFlight` map prevents double-scheduling
   - Correlation env vars: `YOKE_WORKFLOW_ID`, `YOKE_ITEM_ID`, `YOKE_STAGE`, `YOKE_PHASE`, `YOKE_SESSION_ID`, `YOKE_ATTEMPT`
   - Retry backoff: 5s in-memory timer; rate-limit timer from `RateLimitDetectedEvent.resetAt`
   - Concurrency: `effectiveRunning = runningSql + pendingInFlight` (SQLite + inFlight items not yet in DB)

3. Files and Code Sections:

   - **`src/server/api/ws.ts`** — Added `WsClientRegistry` class and wired it into subscribe/unsubscribe/connect handlers.
     ```typescript
     export class WsClientRegistry {
       private readonly clients = new Map<WebSocket, Set<string>>();
       constructor(
         private readonly seqStore: SessionSeqStore,
         private readonly backfillBuffer: BackfillBuffer,
       ) {}
       register(socket: WebSocket): void { /* sets up close listener */ }
       subscribe(socket: WebSocket, workflowId: string): void { ... }
       unsubscribe(socket: WebSocket, workflowId: string): void { ... }
       broadcast(workflowId: string, sessionId: string | null, frameType: ServerFrameType, payload: unknown): void {
         const seq = sessionId ? this.seqStore.next(sessionId) : 0;
         const frame = makeFrame(frameType, payload, { workflowId, ...(sessionId ? { sessionId } : {}), seq });
         if (sessionId) this.backfillBuffer.push(sessionId, frame);
         for (const [socket, subs] of this.clients) {
           if (subs.has(workflowId) && socket.readyState === socket.OPEN)
             socket.send(JSON.stringify(frame));
         }
       }
     }
     ```
     Also updated `WsHandlerContext` to include `registry?: WsClientRegistry`, and updated `handleSubscribe`, `handleUnsubscribe`, `createWsHandler` to call registry methods.

   - **`src/server/api/server.ts`** — Added `WsClientRegistry` to `ServerState`, instantiated and passed to `createWsHandler`:
